Over the past few months, a group of us Minervans came together to explore Korean literature. Our goal was to gain an insider's perspective on Korean culture and history through stories, not just textbooks. And honestly, it was one of the best decisions we made.

It's been an incredible journey — learning about gender norms through *The Vegetarian*, the experience of Korean immigrants in Japan through *Pachinko*, and the 1980s democratic uprising in Korea through *Human Acts*.

If you're heading to Seoul, or if you've already left and want to reflect back, I've compiled mini-reviews of the books we read and loved. Give them a chance! You'd be surprised how much ink and paper can teach you.

---

## *The Vegetarian* — Han Kang

On the surface, *The Vegetarian* is about a woman named Yeong-hye who decides to go vegetarian. But beneath that seemingly simple decision lies a haunting exploration of alienation, control, and the gradual loss of autonomy over one's own body.

Some might say the main character simply "goes mad," but the real question is: why is she losing her mind?

> "It's your body, you can treat it however you please. The only area where you're free to do just as you like. And even that doesn't turn out how you wanted."

Though the book is short, it leaves a lasting impact. Be warned: it contains graphic and sexually charged scenes that are often disturbing, even confusing. They're meant to provoke, to make you question identity, societal roles, and the limits of personal freedom. Don't expect a straightforward plot or a tidy resolution. This novel is more about inhabiting the minds of its characters — especially Yeong-hye — than following their actions. It's about what it means to be human, not what humans should act like.

One criticism is the translation. Reading it with a group, we all agreed that the prose didn't flow very smoothly. Having read other works by Han Kang, I can confidently say the translation doesn't fully capture her poetic voice. That said, the translation and writing improve in the later chapters. So don't give up too early!

---

## *Pachinko* — Min Jin Lee

As a book club, we took our time with this one, reading it slowly over the course of a month and a half. And honestly, it was the right choice. *Pachinko* is the kind of book that pulls you deep into its world. I felt like I was living alongside the characters — Sunja, Isak, Noah, Mozasu, and so many others. I ate with them, grieved with them, and carried them with me long after I closed the book.

The novel follows a Korean family across four generations and nearly a century. It starts by painting a picture of Korea under Japanese colonization, then follows how many Koreans were pushed to move to Japan, hoping for better jobs and living conditions, but finding themselves facing even more hardship than they ever imagined. They were underserved, looked down on, and discriminated against, but still, they built their own communities, found their place, and kept going despite every wall put up against them.

> "Living every day in the presence of those who refuse to acknowledge your humanity takes great courage."

The characters might be fictional, but Min Jin Lee weaves in real oral histories so well that the whole story feels incredibly real. *Pachinko* gives voice to the stories of real Korean immigrants in Japan — their struggles, their strengths, and the generational scars they carry. It shines light on a part of history that's often ignored outside of East Asia.

> "History has failed us, but no matter."

The book might feel intimidating at first because of its length, but by the time you reach the end, you'll wish it were longer. That said, the last third does feel a bit rushed — like the author was trying to tie everything up a little too quickly. But even that doesn't take away from the overall depth and complexity of the characters and story.

The writing is simple and clear, which makes it surprisingly easy to pick up even during busy moments — between classes, during meals, or before bed. So even though it's long, it's very readable.

---

## *Human Acts* — Han Kang

After *Pachinko*, we moved back from Japan to South Korea, picking up at roughly the year *Pachinko* leaves off — the 1980s, during the brutal student uprising known as the Gwangju Massacre.

The book begins by following Dong-ho, a middle schooler volunteering at a makeshift morgue. The following five chapters focus on people who crossed paths with him. As we learn his story, we're confronted with the harsh realities of state violence, censorship, grief, and the haunting aftermath of collective trauma.

> "Is it true that human beings are fundamentally cruel? Is the experience of cruelty the only thing we share as a species?"

After *The Vegetarian*, I thought I was ready for Han Kang's raw and graphic style. I was wrong. This book doesn't hold back. Yes, there are disturbing scenes of torture and death, but *Human Acts* is not just about violence. It's about how deeply that violence echoes through time — through the bodies and memories of those who survived it, or didn't. The characters aren't just fictional; they represent the truth, the ongoing pain that many Koreans still carry.

Fair warning: *Human Acts* is the kind of book you can't — and shouldn't — read in one sitting. It demands emotional stamina. The writing is so vivid and real that you'll need breaks just to process what you've read. The structure can be confusing: each chapter jumps to a new voice, and the connections aren't always obvious at first. But every detail matters. I honestly think it's worth reading more than once. The first time, treat each chapter like its own story. Let yourself feel the raw humanity, the brutality, and the endurance.

In one of our club meetings, we spent an hour trying to map all the characters and their relationships on paper. We struggled a lot, but slowly realized how masterfully Han Kang built it all. That's the beauty of a book club — reading fiction about a context you're not yet familiar with, and sharing it with others who are also exploring a new place alongside you, allows you to really deep dive into your readings.
